---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Health Checks"
  description="Configure HTTP, TCP, and exec health checks per service to gate deployments and drive automatic rollback."
  section="features"
>
  <p>
    Health checks are the gate between starting a new container and switching traffic. Shuttle runs
    checks <strong>remotely via SSH</strong> — <code>curl</code> for HTTP and <code>/dev/tcp</code>
    for TCP — so they reflect actual network reachability on the server, not just process liveness.
    A failed check triggers automatic rollback (if enabled) before the proxy is ever updated.
  </p>

  <h2>Check types</h2>

  <h3>HTTP</h3>
  <p>
    Issues a <code>curl -sf -o /dev/null</code> request to the container's port on the server.
    Passes on any 2xx or 3xx HTTP response.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  web:
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      type: http
      path: /health          # default: /
      interval: 5            # seconds between retries (default: 2)
      timeout: 3             # curl timeout per attempt in seconds
      retries: 5             # total attempts before failure (default: 5)
</code></pre>

  <h3>TCP</h3>
  <p>
    Opens a TCP connection to the container port using bash's <code>/dev/tcp</code> pseudo-device.
    Passes as soon as the port accepts a connection — no HTTP response required. Useful for databases,
    message queues, or any service that doesn't speak HTTP on its main port.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  worker:
    port: 9000
    healthcheck:
      type: tcp
      interval: 5
      timeout: 3
      retries: 5
</code></pre>

  <h3>Exec</h3>
  <p>
    Runs an arbitrary command inside the container via <code>docker exec</code>. Passes when the
    command exits with code 0. Useful for custom readiness scripts or when the health endpoint is on
    a different port than the public one.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">services:
  api:
    healthcheck:
      type: exec
      command: "php artisan health:check"
      interval: 10
      timeout: 5
      retries: 3
</code></pre>

  <h2>Defaults</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Parameter</th>
        <th>Default</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>path</code></td>
        <td><code>/</code></td>
        <td>HTTP only</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>interval</code></td>
        <td><code>2</code>s</td>
        <td>Pause between retry attempts</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>timeout</code></td>
        <td>Falls back to <code>deploy.timeout</code> (default 60s)</td>
        <td>Per-attempt timeout</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>retries</code></td>
        <td><code>5</code></td>
        <td>Total attempts before marking unhealthy</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Readiness delay (blue-green only)</h2>
  <p>
    Some apps need time to bind their port or run initialization before they can accept connections.
    Use <code>deploy.blue_green.readiness_delay</code> to insert a sleep before the first probe:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">deploy:
  blue_green:
    readiness_delay: 3    # wait 3 seconds before the first health probe
</code></pre>

  <h2>Health checks are remote</h2>
  <p>
    Shuttle does not run health checks from your local machine. All probes execute on the remote host
    via SSH:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HTTP</strong>: <code>ssh user@host "curl -sf -o /dev/null -m &lt;timeout&gt; http://127.0.0.1:&lt;port&gt;&lt;path&gt;"</code></li>
    <li><strong>TCP</strong>: <code>ssh user@host "timeout &lt;t&gt; bash -c 'echo &gt; /dev/tcp/127.0.0.1/&lt;port&gt;'"</code></li>
    <li><strong>Exec</strong>: <code>docker exec &lt;container&gt; &lt;command&gt;</code> via SSH</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This ensures that network policies, firewall rules, and container networking on the server are
    validated — not your laptop's connectivity to the host.
  </p>

  <h2>Auto-rollback on failure</h2>
  <p>
    When <code>deploy.auto_rollback: true</code> (the default) and a health check fails:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Blue-green</strong>: the new container is stopped immediately. The old container was never stopped, so traffic is unaffected.</li>
    <li><strong>Rolling</strong>: the failing replica is restored from <code>previous_tag</code> and re-health-checked before the error is thrown.</li>
    <li><strong>Swarm</strong>: Swarm's native rollback triggers automatically when the update monitor detects an unhealthy task. Shuttle surfaces the <code>rollback_completed</code> or <code>rollback_paused</code> state as a deploy error.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>No health check configured</h2>
  <p>
    If a service has no <code>healthcheck</code> block, Shuttle skips the check and proceeds
    directly to the proxy switch. The container is assumed healthy as soon as it starts. This is fine
    for background workers with no public port, but is not recommended for web services.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
